  "prompt": "What function do we use in Java in place of cin>> in C++?",
  "response": "In Java, there is no direct equivalent to `cin >>` from C++, but you can achieve similar functionality using the `Scanner` class from the `java.util` package. The `Scanner` class allows you to read input from various sources, including the standard input (keyboard).\n\nHere\u2019s an example of how to use `Scanner` to read input from the user:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.Scanner;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        // Create a Scanner object to read input from the standard input (keyboard)\n        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);\n\n        // Prompt the user for input\n        System.out.print(\"Enter an integer: \");\n\n        // Read an integer from the user\n        int number = scanner.nextInt();\n\n        // Output the entered number\n        System.out.println(\"You entered: \" + number);\n\n        // Close the scanner to free resources\n        scanner.close();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- **`Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);`**: Creates a `Scanner` object that reads from the standard input (keyboard).\n- **`scanner.nextInt();`**: Reads an integer from the input. Similar methods like `nextDouble()`, `nextLine()`, etc., are available for reading other types of data.\n- **`scanner.close();`**: Closes the `Scanner` object to release any system resources associated with it.\n\n### Common `Scanner` Methods:\n- **`nextInt()`**: Reads an `int`.\n- **`nextDouble()`**: Reads a `double`.\n- **`nextLine()`**: Reads a `String` (until the end of the line).\n- **`next()`**: Reads a single word (until the next whitespace).\n\n### Example with `String` and `double`:\n```java\nimport java.util.Scanner;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);\n\n        System.out.print(\"Enter your name: \");\n        String name = scanner.nextLine();\n\n        System.out.print(\"Enter your height in meters: \");\n        double height = scanner.nextDouble();\n\n        System.out.println(\"Hello, \" + name + \"! Your height is \" + height + \" meters.\");\n\n        scanner.close();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis approach is the Java equivalent of using `cin >>` in C++ for reading user input.",
